ce:section.ce:para:
The 3D UiO-67/NSC was designed as a super adsorbent for selective recognition and effective removal of TC from contaminated water or food samples, and it was synthesized using a solvothermal method with the heterogeneous nucleation effect of NSC nanocomposites (Scheme 1
                        ) [22]. The surface morphologies of the prepared UiO-67 UiO-67/NSC-0.2, and UiO-67/NSC were observed by SEM. The UiO-67 had smooth surfaces and an octahedron structure (Fig. 1
                        a). Compared with pure UiO-67, the morphology of UiO-67/NSC-0.2 was not regular with the shapes of nano-flower and octahedron (Fig. S1), which may result from few NSC-Zr4+-NSC structures in the reaction system. While the used volume of NSC increase to 2.0 ml, the carboxyl groups of BPDC combines with NSC-Zr4+-NSC structure to grow the nanosheet of UiO-67/NSC by self-assembly process. After reaction, the morphology of UiO-67 was changed to a regular flower-like shape with hierarchical structure and was covered with 2D nanosheets (Fig. 1b, and Fig. 1c), implying that heterogeneous nucleation participated in the synthesis process. This also indicated that the morphology of UiO-67 was changed by the addition of a NSC composite in synthesis, and NSC had been combined successfully with UiO-67. The distribution of diameters of UiO-67/NSC that was obtained were analyzed using Nano Measure software. The diameters of UiO-67/NSC were distributed mainly in the range of 280–320 nm (Fig. 1d). This range was smaller than that of parent UiO-67 because the added NSC restricted the spatial growth of UiO-67, and the combination of NSC and Zr4+ ions also limited the formation of a regular octahedron shape [23]. Moreover, TEM analysis was used to illustrate the substance morphologies of UiO-67/NSC and NSC and to clarify the thickness of the nanolayer on the surface of UiO-67/NSC. The size of the UiO-67/NSC was approximately 300 nm with hierarchical structure and coated by 2D sheets, and the diameter of NSC was about 2 nm consistent with the morphology of carbon dot (Fig. S2), which confirmed the combination of CDs with UiO-67. The TEM-EDX and the corresponding elemental mapping was used to confirm the constituent elements of UiO-67/NSC. As shown in Figs. S3 and S4, the elements of 2D sheet and core of UiO-67/NSC were C, Zr, O, N, and S, and the contents of N and S were lower than that of C, Zr and O. Both for C, Zr, O, N and S were distributed uniformly in 2D sheet and nucleus of UiO-67/NSC.

Elemental composition of UiO-67/NSC was also studied by SEM-elemental mapping and EDX analysis. The elements C, Zr, O, N, and S were distributed in the UiO-67/NSC (Fig. 2
                        ), which confirmed the presence of NSC in the novel Zr-MOF-based adsorbent. N and S elements emerging in the EDX spectrum (Fig. S5) also proved the existence of NSC. The PXRD patterns of synthesized UiO-67 and UiO-67/NSC had some common diffraction peaks such as 2θ = 5.4°, 6.5°, and 17.2° (Fig. 3
                        ), and these peaks were the proof that UiO-67 was synthesized successfully and its crystalline structure was well preserved in the UiO-67/NSC [24]. Moreover, the attending of NSC did not destroy the structure of UiO-67, suggesting abundant Zr-OH groups, carboxyl groups, and large specific surface areas of both UiO-67 and NSC may be totally retained.
